Gaelic names containing the element <i>donn</i> ‘brown-haired’ (also meaning ‘chieftain’), for example   Donahue  .","Irish: phonetic Anglicization of <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhnaigh</b>; see   Breheny  ."]}]},{"name":"Juliana","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Julianus</i> (  see  Julian  ), which was revived in England in the 18th century and has been used occasionally ever since."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Munday","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Mundy  .","Irish (Donegal and Sligo): adopted for <b>Mac Giolla Eoin</b> ‘son of the servant of <i>Eoin</i>’ (compare   McGlone  ,   McAloon  ), as a result of confusion of the last part of the name with Irish <i>Luan</i> ‘Monday’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mundy","meanings":["Pet form of   Amanda  , now sometimes used as an independent given name. As a male name it is an Anglicized form of the Jewish name   Mandel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":12,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Juliana Munday Browne was born in 1443, in Stockport, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir Edmund Shaw III. She died on 6 July 1493, in London, Middlesex, England, at the age of 50, and was buried in London, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1443–6 JUL 1493":"1443–6. juuli 1493","1434–1493":"1434–1493","1467–1552":